Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with `CancelCommand` that confirms before navigating

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return; // user chose to stay
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back button in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` only handles the **shell toolbar** button. The Android hardware back button and swipe-back gesture go through `OnNavigating`, so you need a guard there too:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `BackButtonBehavior.Command` replaces the default back action on the toolbar button — you control navigation yourself via `GoToAsync("..")`.
- `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` intercepts hardware/gesture back. The deferral is **required** because `DisplayAlert` is async.
- Check `args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so you only guard back-navigation, not forward navigation.
